\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 How does being directly or proximally impacted by the criminal legal system shape perceptions of what policy carceral citizens deserve? My theoretical starting point is that perceptions of what groups like carceral citizens deserve are often shaped by social constructions about them (Schneider and Ingram 1993). Like stereotypes, these constructions are produced by policy and discourse \'96 both political, cultural, and popular. On the individual level, then, these constructions are often taken up in a heuristic process to form quick judgements about what a target group deserves. Thus, predominant racialized constructions of incarcerated people \'96 \'93thugs,\'94 \'93felons,\'94 or \'93inmates\'94 \'96 suggesting culpable, ungrateful, \'93takers\'94 responsible for their condition of confinement are likely interpolated as undeserving, translating (following Schneider and Ingram) to support for punitive carceral policy.\'a0\
I suggest that contact with the carceral system affects this process (by.../on xyz levels). Applying insights from the policy feedback literature to matters of target deservingness, I suggest that experience with the criminal legal system \'96 including victimization \'96 leads people to more strongly support policies that help incarcerated people, and to more nuanced ways of thinking about the relationship between what a carceral target 'deserves' and what policy is appropriate.\
Contact may inform information about targets, (2) attitudes towards targets, (3) attitudes towards criminal legal institutions, and (3). These factors, I propose, may drive distinct perceptual outcomes and policy preferences between, and more support for policy help across, the three impact groups than "non-impacted" constituencies.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f2\i\b \cf0 Intervening in Target Deservingness
\f0\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf0 By definition, direct impact \'96 incarceration \'96 and proximate impact will change what information about criminal legal targets is available and salient. Someone who is in and knows people in prison has a different array of information than someone who has only seen "prisoners" on TV. In turn, this informational effect could translate to more generous interpretations of CARIN criteria (Oorschot 2000, 2006, Feather 2009). While policy feedback literature shows that many carceral citizens and their networks internalize the clear "undeserving" messages that prison policy sends, it also shows that, across contexts where interactions with the criminal legal system mobilize or demobilize, these experiences shape attitudes towards the state (Anoll et al 2022, Anoll and Israel-Trummel 2019, Walker 2020, Lerman and Weaver 2014). As such, I propose that interactions with the criminal legal system should also shape attitudes towards 
\f3\i targets
\f1\i0  of the state. While some work finds that targets of policy can internalize negative or undeserving constructions (Soss 1999), much of the work on criminal legal contact stresses that demobilization is a product of resource effects or interpretive effects 
\f3\i distinct
\f1\i0  from an \'93undeserving\'94 self-conception (Lerman and Weaver 2014, White 2019). Instead, other work emphasizes that direct contact with the criminal legal system can heighten in-group solidarity (Lerman and Weaver 2014) and mobilize in spite resource and interpretive feedbacks that should be demobilizing, specifically when policy targets reject policy \'93teachings\'94 about their lower civic status as part of a sense of systemic injustice \'96 suggesting a perception that the criminal legal system is less legitimate or authoritative, and of its targets as distinctly deserving (Walker 2020).\
Proximal contact also generates political mobilization despite policy experiences that "should" demobilize (Anoll et al 2022, White 2019b). Anoll\'92s (2022) findings that family of the incarcerated vote at higher rates in states with more stringent carceral disenfranchisement policies suggests that \'93surrogate\'94 mobilization is motivated by a desire to act on behalf a \'93deserving\'94 incarcerated citizen. Her findings with Israel-Trummel (2019) that neighborhood exposure to racially discriminatory policing generate perceptions of institutional 
