\f2\i\b \cf0 Victimization Effects on Deservingness Perceptions
\f0\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf0 While victimization might intuitively drive negative perceptions of carceral citizens, I suggest the relationship is more complex. To be sure, there are clear reasons why victimization may generate undeserving perceptions of and opposition to policies that help carceral targets. Victimization is obviously a salient experience that for many drives negative affect toward those who commit crimes (Ditton et al. 1999). Victims usually engage the criminal legal system because they believe their offender is deserving of punishment, and they are deserving of establishing a sense of safety and justice. But it is also true that to accomplish the latter, victims of violent crime have few other options \'96 including if they know their perpetrator personally or understand their perpetrator to be in need of help. And such overlap in contact is significant (Gebo 2019). Victims of violent crime are disproportionately part of communities most heavily policed and incarcerated, and most victims of violent crime know their offender (Bureau of Justice 2024). An extensive literature shows that people who are incarcerated have disproportionately been victims of crime \'96 one review article cited 31 of 37 papers support this overlap (Jennings et al 2012). While 2% of the general US population report being victims of violent crime, up to 45% of carceral citizens have experienced pre-incarceration physical abuse, and 8.5 to 39.2% of specifically sexual abuse (Azimi et al 2019, Carlson and Shafer 2010, Messina et al 2007, Wolff and Shi 2012, Yoder et al. 2017). Still more experience violence while incarcerated (Wolff et al 2009). Thus, while for many victims the proximity and salience of a criminal may bolster negative social constructions and deservingness perceptions, it might also translate to more nuanced perceptions of culpability and a closer alignment of identity that moderates negative affect.\
Additionally, victims face restrictive social constructions distinct in content but similar in "stickiness" to those of carceral citizens. For example, Lens et al (2014) show that in navigating narrow expectations of "appropriate" emotional responses in the criminal justice process \'96 non-emotional victims risk disbelief while overly emotional victims face judgment \'96 victims experience "secondary victimizations" that foment institutional sketipicism.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f2\i\b \cf0 Contact on Policy Preferences
\f0\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf0 Social construction theory suggests that perceptions of target deservingness translate directly to policy preferences: groups constructed as undeserving receive punitive policy while deserving groups receive beneficial policy (Schneider and Ingram 1993). In this framework, warmer perceptions of incarcerated people's deservingness should predict greater support for policies that help rather than punish them. I therefore hypothesize that 
\f0\b (H2)
\f1\b0  more generous perceptions of carceral citizens' deservingness will predict greater support for assistance-oriented policies and reduced support for punitive policies.\
However, evidence from SoRelle and Laws (2023) and others suggests the relationship between deservingness perceptions and policy support may not be straightforward in all contexts. The criminal legal domain may have unique dynamics where perceptions of groups and support for policies directed at them operate through different mechanisms.\
While direct and proximal contact likely increase perceptions of deservingness (H1), there are reasons to expect additional direct effects on policy preferences.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Direct and Proximal Contact Effects on Policy Preferences\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Policy feedback literature indicates that contact with the criminal legal system shapes not only perceptions of targets but also attitudes toward institutions and policies. Lerman and Weaver (2014) demonstrate that court, police, and prison encounters foster government distrust and altered civic identity. Walker (2020) shows how carceral citizens develop a sense of "systemic injustice" that shapes their policy views beyond simple in-group solidarity.\
Similarly, proximal contact generates institutional feedback effects that may directly influence policy preferences. Anoll and Israel-Trummel (2019) find that neighborhood exposure to discriminatory policing generates perceptions of institutional illegitimacy that shape policy attitudes independent of perceptions about policed individuals.\
These findings suggest that carceral contact may affect policy preferences through mechanisms beyond deservingness perceptions alone. I therefore hypothesize that 
\f0\b (H4)
\f1\b0  direct and proximate experiences with incarceration will lead to greater support for decarceral or assistance-oriented policies, even after controlling for deservingness perceptions.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Victimization and Policy Preferences\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Similar complexity characterizes the relationship between victimization and policy preferences. While victims are often portrayed in public discourse as supporting punitive policies (Levine and Russell), research indicates victimization does not increase punitiveness (Kleck and Jackson 2016). Instead, victims appear more concerned with improved compensation (Shapland 1984) and addressing root causes of crime (ASJ 2024)\
The experiences of "expectancy violation" and secondary victimization documented by Lens et al. (2014) suggest victims may develop institutional skepticism that directly shapes their policy views beyond their perceptions of perpetrators. Victims who experience the criminal justice system as imposing restrictive narratives may develop policy preferences focused on systemic reform rather than individual punishment.\
Evidence that victimization increases political participation (Bateson 2012), including in resource-intensive community organizing, further suggests victims develop nuanced policy perspectives that may not align with simple punitive impulses. Therefore, I extend H4 to include victims, suggesting victimization experience will also predict greater support for assistance-oriented policies beyond what is explained by deservingness perceptions.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Summary of Theoretical Framework\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 This theoretical framework recognizes multiple pathways through which carceral contact may shape both deservingness perceptions and policy preferences. While the deservingness literature suggests a straightforward relationship (deservingness \uc0\u8594  policy preferences), policy feedback literature indicates contact creates institutional effects that may independently influence policy views. By examining both pathways simultaneously, this study contributes to our understanding of how direct experience with policy shapes political attitudes and preferences.\
